product_title: Motorola Roadster Bluetooth In-Car Speakerphone
review_body: I spend a lot of time in my car for work, so I've moved past the radio and listen to audiobooks to break the monotony of mile after mind-numbing mile of flat, Midwestern interstate.  After listening to the entire 'Harry Potter' series on headphones, I decided I needed to find a better way and purchased a Roadster.    Since my primary motivation to buy the Roadster was the A2DP streaming through the FM transmitter, that was the first thing I tested, and I was satisfied.  I have used FM transmitters before, and I had pretty low expectations particularly because I live in a major city.  However, 87.9 FM tended to be very reliable and I experienced only sporadic static.  This improved a little when I switched from my 2004 Honda Civic to my wife's 2006 VW Jetta but was still present occasionally.  As far as FM transmitters go, this one was ahead of the pack based on past experiences.    The phone function was good, but not great, hence the title of this review and my grade of four stars.  On the listening end, I had no problem hearing the other person.  The FM transmitter's performance during calls was about the same as in A2DP mode.  The Roadster lost it's star on the talking end; I had several complaints about people not being able to hear me.  They tended to be 800 numbers and other business calls, whereas my friends and family seemed to be able to hear me well more often than not.  I'm not sure if that's because they were more tolerant of small interruptions or because of something on the receiving end with business calls.      For reference purposes, my Civic was totaled in an accident about a month after I bought the Roadster.  I bought a 2011 Chevrolet Cruze with built-in Bluetooth to replace it, and those whom I've asked have all said they can hear me better in the Cruze than they could in the Civic.  I'm sure there are several factors (road noise, distance to mic, etc.) that factor in, but I thought it was worth noting.    Overall, the Roadster is a good productand worth the price, especially for people that spend a lot of time in the car.

product_title: Jensen VX3022 A/V Receiver with DVD, 6.2-Inch Touch Screen with Bluetooth
review_headline: You get what you pay for.
review_body:
So this was listed as the #1 bestseller on Amazon, and I didn't want to pay a higher price on a pioneer for the upgrade on a relatively older car (5 years old) so decided to take the plunge.
Here are the drawbacks I noticed once i started using it -
1. Navigation only says turn left in 50 feet etc. - doesn't read out any street names - you need to look that up on the screen. I called Jensen support and they said no text-speech available to announce street names.
2. Even in verbose mode the navigation announcement is not efficient and timely - use google navigation and then this - you'll see what I mean - it's a big step down from the navigation on google maps.
3. There is a lag in the GPS tracking - it says turn left in some feet when you're already at the turn - so you need to watch out - to be specific it was off by like 25 feet.
4. Software is average - sometimes the buttons lag when ur typing.
5. When you turn on the radio, the default volume level is pretty high!! It made me jump many a times whenever I turned on the radio on a quiet evening drive - immediately you will need to lower the volume - unless you are the types who likes to blast radio lol.

Looking at all this, I decided to spend an extra 250-300 and buy a pioneer instead. Have filed return.

product_title: Belkin Sync Cable for Apple iPod
review_headline: When it's time for a new sync cable
review_body:
I have a lot of Apple products that I sync. I have an [[ASIN:B005SSB4NG Apple iPhone 4S 32GB (Black) - AT&T]], an [[ASIN:B00746VKG6 Apple iPad MD368LL/A (64GB, Wi-Fi + AT&T 4G, Black) NEWEST MODEL]], and a number of old iPods. They all connect to my [[ASIN:B007471PZQ Apple MacBook Pro MC975LL/A 15.4-Inch Laptop with Retina Display (NEWEST VERSION)]] or one of two [[ASIN:B001U0OH8K Apple iMac MB419LL/A 24-Inch Desktop]] and even [[ASIN:B006Y443TU Pioneer AVIC-X940BT In-Dash Navigation AV Receiver with 6.1\\" WVGA Touchscreen and Built-In Bluetooth]]. So what this means is that my devices are constantly being charged or synched.

Obviously, I love Apple produced, but here's my beef. The 3\\" sync cables are too small and not rugged.

The Belkin cable is very sturdy and is a foot longer. This can make a difference depending on how and where you you use it. For instance I charge my iPad at night. If the cable by my bed is too short I have to unplug my iPad to use it. All that unplugging wears on the cable and soon I find myself out buying another.

With this cable, two problems solved.
